Q: ASP.NET Core migrating database issue A: <p>For my case, this was the solution:</p>
<p>I adjusted the order of the code, made sure I added the controllers and DB context before building the app and it fixed the issue</p>
<p>After</p>
<pre class="lang-cs prettyprint-override"><code>// Add services to the container
builder.Services.AddControllers();
builder.Services.AddDbContext&lt;AppDbContext&gt;(options =&gt; options.UseSqlite(dbPath));

var app = builder.Build();
app.MapControllers();
app.Run();
</code></pre>

Q: How can I use two pointers to an interface to invoke the correct function that takes implementing classes as arguments? A: <p>As Jarod42 proposed, <code>std::variant</code> is a good way to go in such a case.</p>
<p>However, a potential flaw might occur in case one forgets to define a specific <code>intersect</code> overload, e.g.</p>
<pre><code>bool intersect(const Circle&amp; s1, const Circle&amp; s2) { return true; }
bool intersect(const Circle&amp; s1, const Line&amp;   s2) { return true; }
bool intersect(const Line&amp;   s1, const Circle&amp; s2) { return true; }
//OUPS, forgot this one... bool intersect(const Line&amp;   s1, const Line&amp;   s2) { return true; }
</code></pre>
<p>As proposed, one defines an overload with variants:</p>
<pre><code>bool intersect(const Shape&amp; shape1, const Shape&amp; shape2) {
    return std::visit([](const auto&amp; s1, const auto&amp; s2){ return intersect(s1, s2); }, shape1, shape2);
}
</code></pre>
<p>The following calls will be ok:</p>
<pre><code>intersect (Circle(),Circle());
intersect (Circle(),Line());
intersect (Line(),Circle());
</code></pre>
<p>but this one will crash at runtime:</p>
<pre><code>intersect (Line(),Line());
</code></pre>
<p>because the arguments <code>s1</code> and <code>s2</code> of the lambda function provided to <code>std::visit</code> will be of type <code>Line</code> and <code>Line</code>; since there is no defined overload of <code>intersect</code> with types <code>Line</code> and <code>Line</code>, the overload with variants is the only candidate and then will be (recursively) called with the two lines converted as <code>Shape</code> objects. We have thus an infinite recursion that will lead to a crash because of a stack overflow.</p>
<p>Actually, forgetting to define an overload might happen quite easily in case one has more than two classes to handle (i.e. more kinds of shapes in the example).</p>
<p>A solution would be to have a distinct name than <code>intersect</code> for the overload with <code>Shape</code> arguments (see <a href="https://godbolt.org/z/MsqqE9jro" rel="nofollow noreferrer">here</a>) or define the <code>intersect</code> methods inside the classes (see <a href="https://godbolt.org/z/9o3dn67zb" rel="nofollow noreferrer">here</a>). By doing this, we will get a compile error and not a crash during execution, which is obviously a much better option.</p>
